Title: Marvel's Ant-Man - Trailer 1
Comment:
Great movie, but to me I feel like Antman was always just a half-assed Marvel superhero. It's like Stan Lee just wanted a Superhero who could grow or shrink. Not a whole lot of science on how his powers work. 

They tried to explain it in the film, but there were too many scenes that took place that contradicted how exactly he keeps his mass. For example, when he shrinks for the first time and he falls onto the bathroom tile, it breaks. Or when he lands on the car, it leaves a tiny dent. But in a different scene (1:25 to be exact) we see him running down the barrel of a gun. If he keeps his mass, the person holding the gun would not be able to support that weight. Also during the finally where Hank Pym's keychain tank is revealed to be real, how the hell would Hank have been carrying this tank in his pocket? 

Just some things that always bothered me about Antman.

Title: Marvel's Ant-Man - Trailer 1
Comment: Extremely charming, refreshing, sweet and colorful film with great action, performances and direction. Paul Rudd is perfectly cast as Scott Lang Ant Man, i liked the way he portrayed it because he did a perfect blend of drama, humour and badassery. Michael Douglas was great as dr. Pym and supporting cast including the villain did a great job. It is  a perfect example how you can make superhero film that is not bloated and overproduced, in this case bigger is not better, little is better - no pun intended. Less is more here and i liked it. It is pretty much fast paced, jokes worked, movie doesn't feel forced despite taking time to explain stuff and develop characters and in the end it is a big plus for Marvel after doing same old for couple of years. 4.5/5

Title: Marvel's Ant-Man - Trailer 1
Comment:
So I just came back from this movie. A good one though couldn't compare to others in MCU like Avenger or Guardians.
The pros:
+ Cool and fun, true to MCU's spirit.
+ Good performances, especially Paul Rudd.
+ Visually great. The ants look amazing.
The cons:
- Choppy, full of cliche and plot holes story. Also the Father - Daughter conflict subplot is unconvincing, and kinda unnecessary
- Some jokes, especially the end where they try to set Ant man up to join the Avengers fell flat, and somewhat confusing.
- Underdeveloped characters.

Overall I would say a 7 out of 10 movie. Entertaining enough, but I probably wouldn't watch more than once.

Title: Marvel's Ant-Man - Trailer 1
Comment:
Ant-Man is not a comic that I am very familiar with, and I can already tell that it is being handled pretty strangely and arguably poorly, given the choice to use Lang over Pym, and Pym's age, and the removal of Pym's affiliation with Ultron, the production history thus far and probably a few more things still that more die hard fans could point out. But it still looks like a good time. Not a far cry from Guardians of the Galaxy. I never would have thought I'd be a fan of a talking raccoon before that one. This still looks like a comic book adaptation and I appreciate that it isn't trying to take itself too seriously like DC's current projects with 80% of it's cast looking not even a little bit like their comic book counterparts.

Personally, I would have gone with Michael Rosenbaum for Scott Lang. He seems closer to the images that I find of Scott Lang in the comics, and from his time voicing the Flash on the Justice League Animated Series, I know he has that same type of humor that you see Paul Rudd going for in these trailers. But I do like Paul Rudd too, I just about died laughing at the "Role Models" movie that he is in.

That said, unlike BvS or Suicide Squad or Fantastic Four, I will definitely be going to see this. The fact that the casting for this film clearly wasn't driven by politically correct pandering is both very refreshing and something that I can wholeheartedly support. Nothing makes me face palm harder than watching Hollywood cast one or two cast members like they are going for visual accuracy, just to abandon that practice entirely for the rest of the cast so that they can pander to people who will only come see the movie if there is black/brown/lgbt/feminist/etc representation in it.

Maybe this film will be a hit, maybe it will be a flop. All I know is it appeals to me far more than the shit casting that DC's projects have.

Hopefully they find some clever way to tie Ant-Man/Scott Lang in to the broader Marvel Universe since the whole Pym-Ultron bridge has been burned. I love the little tie in stuff, like the Avengers article in the news paper in the Daredevil Netflix series. Hopefully this does not land on the Iron Man 3 side of the MCU spectrum.

Title: Marvel's Ant-Man - Trailer 1
Comment:
For those that struggle to convince their friends that Ant-Man's abilities are at-all interesting, or those who themselves find the powers silly or pointless,¬†whether discussing the original Hank Pym or the Pym-taught Scott Lang, consider the following:

1. Need armor? Patch together 100+ layers of shrunken Kevlar (or any combination
of materials you can imagine) and you are at the very least durable, potentially
indestructible.

2. Need energy? Shrink a building-sized power plant with matching fuel supply to
fit in the palm of your hand. An array of 10,000+ of Stark's arc reactors anyone?

3. Need computing power? Shrink a full super computer complex and you have a souped up iPhone. Combine and arrange any number of shrunken components of your choice or design and the possibilities grow tremendously. Can you imagine how many miniaturized components the Ant-Man helmet alone could contain? The helmet can do much more than help communicate with ants.

4. Pym is creative and intelligent. He discovered the Pym particles he uses for re-sizing and invented ways to isolate and harness them. There is a reason why it was Pym that created Ultron in the comics as opposed to Tony Stark, Bruce Banner or even Reed Richards. Stark is the scientist heroes go to for upgrades; Pym is the scientist Stark goes to for upgrades. Any idea you can come up with, he could take it to the next level.

Remember, the Ant-man suit is simply a subset of the generalizable and flexible Pym technology; Micro-sized super-villain prisons, Ultron and indirectly The Vision are some of the other most notable applications from the comics. I won't even expand on the growth/Giant-Man aspect of the character or the interactions with Wasp.¬†

With this perspective, it is easy to see why Ant-man is not only a worthy member of the Avengers, but a defining member. Do those adamantium/vibranium wielding warriors like Wolverine or Captain America look so much cooler than Ant-man anymore? (They're still cool, and yes, they have other characteristics that make them interesting and relevant.)

TL;DR
Shrink whatever you want, build whatever you can imagine with the tiny parts, leverage the possibilities; Profit.

Comment:
Spoiler territory:Ok, the first mid credits scene: For Ant-Man

Hank Pym (Michael Douglas) gives the WASP costume with wings to Hope Van Dyne (Evangeline Lilly). Hank explains to Hope what happened to Hope's mother Janet Van Dyne.

Final credits scene:

This one leads into Captain America: Civil War. 

The scene has Captain America, The Falcon, and The Winter Soldier. Cap and Falcon have located The Winter Soldier to a remote location where The Winter Soldier is tied up.

Falcon asks Cap "Should I call Stark?"

Cap replies "No."

Falcon replies "I know who to call." Implying Ant-Man.

In case you didn't know, Falcon is in Ant-Man in a few key scenes.

There ya have it.

Comment: An Ant Man movie really? ¬†Ant Man should be nothing more than a comic relief character in an Avengers movie if he's even worthy of being put in one. ¬†Marvel/Disney is just going to keep putting out this kind of shit because for some reason people keep going to see this kind of movie despite the lack of effort put into it. ¬†This movie looks similar to Guardians of the Galaxy which a lot of people liked including myself, but the only reason people liked that was because it wasn't your average superhero movie. ¬†Most people didn't know who the hell Starlord or Rocket Raccoon were before seeing the movie and enjoyed the movie because it wasn't just another superhero that had been retold time after time again each time just with a few different quirks like Superman or Spiderman. ¬†This movie is the average superhero movie: dead parents, cool cgi and special effects, secret lab left from dead parents. ¬†It just has a few funny phrases from Paul Rudd every now and then which makes it just a tiny bit different. ¬†Do yourself a favor, don't waste your hard earned money on this over cgi'd garbage because I promise you it will not be a good movie. ¬†It'll get average reviews at best.

Title: Marvel's Ant-Man - Trailer 1
Comment:
I don't read comics so I don't know what the idea is behind this Ant Man, but if it uses the same "theory" as "Honey I Shrunk the Kids" where they are reducing the space between atoms and "shrinking" him, he would still *weigh* the same he weighed at full size, so he'd be a 180lb Ant-sized person, with the same strength as before as well.¬† There's no way that guy could hold his gun with 180lbs of weight on it.

There would also be no real need to say he has super human strength as an Ant sized person would still be able to lift the same, so if someone were to step on him, not only would it NOT squish him (stepping on a person's chest to kill an ant is barely going to hurt a person), he could then pretty much toss the guy over.¬† To be further realistic though, leverage plays a big role when trying to flip someone over, and an ant sized person would have no leverage, so it would be harder.

That's just my theory on the whole thing.

Title: Marvel's Ant-Man - Trailer 1
Comment: You'd think many would fear this movie being Marvel Studio's first true failure (Hulk didn't fail it just didn't do well, similar to Thor: The Dark World), given the source material. But honestly, after watching Daredevil, Guardians of The Galaxy, Agent Carter, Winter Soldier, Iron Man 3, Thor, etc it's clear that Marvel can pull off any genre. The superhero genre doesn't exist. It's superheroes in different genres. The Iron Man Trilogy are tech thrillers, Hulk was a monster fighting movie akin to Godzilla, Captain America and Agent Carter were period pieces, Guardians of The Galaxy was a Sci-Fi Adventure, Thor was a fantasy, Avengers (and AOU) is a straight out action thriller, Ant-Man is said to be a heist movie, Daredevil is a drama, Winter Soldier was a spy movie, Doctor Strange is said to be a horror movie, and even then we'll still have other movies: Civil War, Ragnarok, Inhumans, Captain Marvel, Black Panther, Spectacular Spider-Man, Guardians of the Galaxy 2, and Infinity War Parts 1 & 2. As well as other TV shows: AKA Jessica Jones, Luke Cage, Iron Fist, Agents of SHIELD season 3, Agent Carter season 2, Daredevil season 2, etc. Yea, I don't think Marvel Studios is going to fall anytime soon. The next 5 years are a comic book fan's dream.

Comment:
Umm, I have followed Ant-Man FROM DAY ONE. Yep more than 40 years. Comics are not movies. Adaptation for movies ALWAYS leaves so much to be desired...the expense of making a movie. You would think that by now, they could just automate the creation of CGI, like ordering a pizza from a smart-machine with a bottomless database, but no.
¬† ¬† ¬†A weekly TV show always does better at making a comic more to life, even more to science. In a movie you HAVE to go for broad strokes...letting women punch men, which in real life, would get her GUTTED! Stuff like that.¬†
¬† I really feel, that web-based movies, are the best of both worlds, TV-like regular presentation but the costs are, or can be, FAR lower...better CGI, why? TV's do NOT have plug-ins, software plug-ins! On the web, SHOWS-ABOUT-THE-SHOWS and advertising revenue opportunities so good that rich-content-advertising could actually have...DRUM ROLL PLEASE...their own channel/movie!
¬† ¬†Movies? Please, Have some loving mercy for old-school presentations, if you can.

Comment:
I like how they took a character that was largely against violence and even refused to fight even when his team needed him at certain points, leaving the avengers because he couldn't handle the damage he had done when he created the ultrons, and turned him into now a slightly diluted iron man that can shrink.¬†

Would just like to point out, that completely changing a character but keeping the name doesn't mean you have the same character, it means you ran out of ideas because you tried making a movie out of a largely passive character that was down right against fighting, and that's not a good thing.

It's not being different to change your story that was originally deep and complex and boiling it down and cutting the fat until it fits into a jar, it's being lazy because you left out the one character in the new avengers film that is the sole catalyst for the new films entire being (the ultrons).

Comment: Looks really fun...but that's it. I'm kinda surprised that despite the great humor (which let's be real here people, isn't the script itself but just what's probably left over from the Edgar Right days, which Marvel, I'm still angry at you for), it still looks really bland. It's like all the issues of the MCU have been distilled down into one film. Uninteresting human characters, bland and rehashed plots, and for a franchise about a connected universe, there is a total lack of consequences. Hopefully Phase 3 changes these issues, but for now, even GotG felt like the same plot as EVERY OTHER MOVIE IN THIS FRANCHISE, just in a more fun coating. It's funny that the best of the MCU isn't even in theaters anymore (Daredevil is amazing!).

I recognize the importance of building and maintaining the shared cinematic universe, and yeah, Ant Man seems comparatively small (that's not a pun, I swear) to just about everyone else save maybe Speedball in terms of possible import. But if they can make this cool and fun and up-to-snuff, and it certainly looks like they can, I say, so what?
Take Ant Man and make a awesome, funny movie if you know you can, because even if it doesn't contribute a whole lot to the wider shared universe (though no-one expected Iron Man to hint at SHIELD and the Avengers when it did, so who knows), if it's good and fun, we'll all be better of for it.¬†

I actually kind of hope they don't try and shove in universe-building just to get it in there and make Ant Man seem relevant to the rest of the MCU. That shoving in of the universe really kinda brought down Iron Man 2 and Guardians, to an extent (moreso to an extent with Guardians, because we do need to see a bit of Thanos before Infinity Wars, but he also really kind of subsumed Ronan as the big bad, which he technically could do, but making the main villain of the film rather subservient to a mostly off-screen villain rarely works well).

Ant Man, I think, could easily have the same problem of them trying to cram in universe-building stuff to sort of justify the existence of the movie, however briefly-seen yet overshadowing said crammed stuff is, and that would be a shame. It would be a shame because this looks like it could be something on the scale of Iron Man 1; something with the truly perfect blend of seriousness and silliness, that strikes that perfect tone and story for a true, unabashed, unashamed super hero film. Guardians and Winter Soldier came damn close to that ideal, but those were as much space opera and spy flick as they were superhero films, dragged down ever so slightly by the conventions of their subgenres. The Thors and the other Iron Men were alright, but they were less tight and more burdened, carrying the weight of establishment and continuation while at times forgetting some key aspects (every portrayal of Iron Man since 1 has forgotten he grew out of his irreverent, doesn't-think-long-term shithead phase (mostly) halfway through the first movie, while Odin in Dark World seemed much less diplomatic and reasonable and Odin-like, for lack of a better term, purely so Thor could be in the right on what to do about who to love and fight and how). Iron Man 1 was pure, perfect super hero greatness on scale we never comprehended before, and we haven't truly had a solo Marvel film live up to that standard since. It's come close, inarguably, but it's also always stopped just short. We could get that again here, I feel like.

Title: Marvel's Ant-Man - Trailer 1
Comment:
people keep saying this movies gonna be great cause marvel got it right with guardians, so what do theyhave to fear. well, dont give guardians so much credit, in this line of thinking. people like to jump on that band wagon saying "look, marvel can make a wierd cosmic comic book that nobodys heard of into a hit. so therefore theyre unstoppable!" but thats only partially true. the success of that movie was NOT in its translation of the guardians comic...its in the sheer knowledge of how badly we all needed a new "star wars" type film. its successful because it was a well done space opera. the fact that they used guardians as a vehicle for it, played nearly zero factor....remember, NOBODY knew who the guardians were. even die hard comic book fans like myself, only knew them by name. im a super sweaty nerd with comics and even i couldnt have told you anything about them. jeez, even look at the characters. starlord=luke/with a bit of han, ¬†green bitch=liea, ¬†groot=chewbacca, ¬†rocket= chewbacca but also with a splash of han. ¬†blue and black bad guy=darth, ¬†thanos= the emporor.¬†
¬† ¬†antman , as much as i want it to be awesome, does not look good. it doesnt look horrible, but nothing from marvel will look horrible in a trailer. ¬†im pretty sure this is gonna be the first marvel movie that doesnt crush at the box office, the tone is all over the place, it has some really hokey action scenes where they are far too comic-bookey and some even going into the slapstick realm (train scene). whatever money this movie makes will be in the first weekend. after that its gonna tank in the numbers and fall away. i hope im wrong, but im calling it. this one, unfortunately, is gonna be the first marvel movie that nobody really cares for. bad direction and the practical effects and even cgi look a little sub-par for a marvel film. if you count avengers as a 10 and iron man 3 as a 6 or a 7, id have to say this one would probably come in at a round a 4 maybe a 5. marvel will just put out another movie and that will be the end of antman. hell never be back.

Comment:
Another generic action movie with superheroes?? That's what I'm getting. But it's Marvel... They're all about levity. But there seem to be TOO much Superhero movies. I think it would be better for Marvel to not make that many movies. Many of them will be generic and one dimensional.

I'm both a fan of film and comics. I'd rather not see some of my favorite comic book characters be tainted by mediocre/bad movies. But it seems like anything passes for other comic book fans these days... No standard or appreciation for the art-forms it seems all they have to be is "cool" and geeky enough.

I rant a lot about this but I feel like DC is trying to do the same thing. Instead of pushing for a more serious approach like the NOlan films, they're going for mindless action and zero depth. Just pumping out films like they're products... I had high hopes for MoS but it just ended up being a very boring film with no depth and intelligence. Poor directing from Snyder in the end.

I sincerely hope comic book movies not get treated like garbage by the film industry.

Title: Marvel's Ant-Man - Trailer 1
Comment:
Personally don't understand why people think Ant-Man is stupid. I mean, sure the name sounds goofy, but the abilities, powers, the creature and character are pretty bad ass (AT LEAST IN MY OPINION). Have you seen what Ants can do, what they have achieved? Do you know that Marvel was developing this film ever since the times of the first Iron Man? Do you know that Ant-Man was a founding Avenger? Do you know that Hank Pym created Ultron? Do you know that he increases in size as well, becoming giant man? Do you know that his character is very complex and has gone through many controversial changes? Do you even know anything about the character? If the answer to all these questions is no, then you shouldn't judge the character so strongly before seeing him. If the answer is yes, then I can understand why you are not inclined to like the character. As for the movie itself, I shall only sincerely judge it after it comes out, and I hope you do the same.

Btw, name wise, Ant-Man isn't any less cheesy than Spider-Man or Bat-Man. It's the legacy of the characters that matter.

Title: Marvel's Ant-Man - Trailer 1
Comment: Okay! This is what I am talking about, new powers! I love the Avengers movie (It's my favourite movie of all time) but¬†you have to admit that with powers it is lacking, a guy who flies, a guy with super strength and a shield, another guy with super strength but a hammer instead of shield which he sometimes uses to shoot lightning or launch into the air, a big guy with super strength, a guy with a bow and arrow, a woman with pistols, not saying it's bad it's just we haven't had that much different powers, guardians of the galaxy is the same, a strong guy, a great fighter, a guy with guns, a racoon with guns (rocket is still badass though) the only exception there is Groot, I'm not complaining I'm just saying how great it is now that we are getting to more varied powers, super speed, magic, earth quakes, teleporting, spider powers, and of course shrinking, this is what I like, varied powers and heroes teaming up with these varied powers and using them together, to be fair though, a lot of the heroes with all the varied powers are or were owned by other companies, xmen, fantastic four, spiderman and ghost rider is what I'm mainly talking about, luckily now marvel have spiderman (sort of) and ghost rider back, xmen is so far fine with fox and while I do want xmen in the mcu, fox is doing okay with the franchise right now and I would like them to at tie up all loose ends before stopping, but fantastic four, yeah they need to just stop and give the rights back to marvel there, but anyway enough ranting, now that all these heroes are now getting more varied powers than just flight and super strength or no powers at all, the mcu is getting even better¬†and we'll probably get even better fights (I recently finally watched the new spongebob movie and I will say, the powers in that movie are awesome! they use them competently, and they are varied, that was a great example of different powers all mixed together, another great example is xmen days of future past with all the future fights, that imo is one of the best uses of varied powers mixed together in any comic book movie I have seen so far!) but back to what I was talking about, now that we have shrinking, it's definitely gonna lead to some awesome fight scenes and I so can not wait! Plus I cannot wait for Antman teaming up with other heroes so I can finally have my dream fight scene with different varied powers in infinity war!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!

Title: Marvel's Ant-Man - Trailer 1
Comment: how is this interesting? this movie is taking the american superhero craze to an absurd extreme. not only are you fed the same explosions and the same characters as the 50,000 other superheroes in the last decade, you now expected to pretend you are entertained by a man who associates with with ants and dresses like one, who shrinks to the size of ants while maintaining his physical strength as if he were yet a full size human. how is this funny? how is this interesting? if it were portrayed as being an allegory for something else entirely, then maybe it would've been interesting, maybe it would have comedic value. but there are adults making these movies, adults who expect other adults to pat them on their heads for thinking up of something as utterly absurd and childish as this. if a 5 year old told me the plot of antboy as a story he thought of himself, then i'd pat his head and compliment him for his creativity, but how am i supposed to react to an adult trying to convey this idea as content meant for a mature audience?
